2. Their Concluſion contains more then was in the Premiſes, for their arguments had only aimed to prove, 
                     that mens Apprehenſions of things Spiritual were not in their power: So that their Diverſity was unavoidable;
                   but when they conclude, they joyn with theſe apprehenſions the "Exerciſe of their Conſcience, of which there was not one word in the premiſes. And as their way of arguing is fallacious, ſo are the propoſitions themſelves not true; for
